There&#39;s two issues: 

* getters/setters are not called directly
* Self-referencing getters

**getters/setters are not called directly**

Getters are not called like methods, so they won&#39;t be called like `wp.getTitle()`. Instead, they are called when _accessing_ the variable. So just doing `wp.Title` is enough to call the getter. 

Similarly, the setter is called when assigning a value like so:

    wp.Title = &quot;Stephen King&quot;

**Self-referencing getters**

After the above issue is fixed, you might have another issue. `this.title` and `this.author` are the properties that hold the values, according to your `constructor`. When the respective getter for the `Title` and `Author` (note the uppercase here) are called, they are effectively calling themselves and will cause a max call stack error. 

There&#39;s no such thing as private, class properties so a lot of people like to prefix variables that are intended to be private with an underscore. This might help keep the confusing down when using similarly named getters, setters, and properties.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

        function makeBook() {
          &quot;use strict&quot;;
          class Book {
            constructor(title, author) {
              this.title = title;
              this.author = author;
            }
            get Title() {
              // lowercase version to ref the property
              return &quot;Title: &quot; + this.title;
            }
            set Title(newTitle) {
              this.title = newTitle;
            }
            get Author() {
              // lowercase version to ref the property
              return &quot;Author: &quot; + this.author;
            }
            set Author(newAuthor) {
              this.author = newAuthor;
            }
          }
          return Book;
        }

        var Book = makeBook();

        var pp = new Book(&quot;Pride and Prejudice&quot;, &quot;Jane Austin&quot;);

        var h = new Book(&quot;Hamlet&quot;, &quot;William Shakespear&quot;);

        var wp = new Book(&quot;War and Peace&quot;, &quot;Leo Tolstoy&quot;);

        console.log(wp.title); // returns &quot;war and peace&quot;

        wp.title = &quot;Peace And War&quot;

        console.log(wp.title) // returns &quot;peace and war&quot;

        // remove the &quot;get&quot; prefix
        console.log(wp.Title)

        // remove the &quot;get&quot; prefix
        console.log(wp.Author)

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

You don&#39;t need the `makeBook()` function at all, just declare the class.

Your getters are trying to access themselves not the attribute so they are endlessly recusing and &quot;Stack Overflowing&quot;. This.title should be lowercase for example

    get Title() {
      return &quot;Title: &quot; + this.title;
    }

So I think you want


    class Book {
      constructor(title, author) {
        this.title = title;
        this.author = author;
      }
      get Title() {
        return &quot;Title: &quot; + this.title;
      }
      set Title(newTitle) {
        this.title = newTitle;
      }
      get Author() {
        return &quot;Author: &quot; + this.author;
      }
      set Author(newAuthor) {
        this.author = newAuthor;
      }
    }
  
    var pp = new Book(&quot;Pride and Prejudice&quot;, &quot;Jane Austin&quot;);

    var h = new Book(&quot;Hamlet&quot;, &quot;William Shakespear&quot;);

    var wp = new Book(&quot;War and Peace&quot;, &quot;Leo Tolstoy&quot;);

